Runs `cargo-machete` to detect unused Cargo dependencies across the workspace and reports each finding as a `FAIL:` line to stderr; exits nonzero if any unused dependency is found or the tool errors.

A missing `cargo-machete` binary is a hard `FAIL` (with an install hint), not a skipped check — deliberately different from tools that degrade gracefully, because this check's whole job is asserting "no unused deps," so silently skipping would make ctx-verify's pass look meaningful when it wasn't. Same posture as `cycle_check.sh`.

Takes one optional arg, the workspace root (default `.`), and `cd`s into it before running.

Parses `cargo machete`'s stdout+stderr via `awk`, expecting its exact report shape: a header line `<crate> -- <path/Cargo.toml>:` followed by tab-indented dep names. Each dep line becomes `FAIL: <path> unused dependency '<dep>'`. If `cargo machete` exits nonzero but the awk parse yields zero findings (e.g., it couldn't read a manifest), emits a generic `FAIL: cargo machete failed` fallback so errors are never silently swallowed. Tracks pass/fail via a `FAIL` flag rather than trusting `cargo machete`'s own exit code directly, since that code conflates "found unused deps" with "tool error."